      "Sure; the `update` returns an object that's queriable with all the existing ReQL operators, so you could do:\r\n\r\n```\r\n   User.get_table() \\\r\n             .get(self.id) \\\r\n             .update(return_changes = True, \r\n                {'reward_amount' :r.row['reward_amount'].default(0)+amount}) \\\r\n             [\"changes\"][\"new_val\"][\"reward_amount\"] \\\r\n             .run(User.get_conn())\r\n```\r\n\r\n(Although that may need some slight whitespace tweaking to work with Python syntax; I'm not sure.)\r\n\r\nClosing because this isn't a bug, but feel free to continue to ask questions here."
